WPA2 Handshake Capture: Home Lab

Overview:
  Full offensive WiFi workflow. Fresh Kali, Alfa AWUS036AXM, my own GL.iNet GL-MT3000 lab router.
  Hardware to captured handshake, start to finish.

Hardware:
  Attack machine: MSI GT72, bare metal Kali
  Adapter: Alfa AWUS036AXM, WiFi 6E, MT7921AU chipset
  Target: GL.iNet GL-MT3000, SSID "Home Lab 2G"

What Broke First
  Fresh Kali did not ship with MT7921AU firmware. Adapter appeared in lsusb but monitor mode failed
  silently. One package fixed it:
      sudo apt install firmware-misc-nonfree -y

  Confirmed with dmesg:
      mt7921u: registered new interface driver

  Second problem was Speakup. Kernel screen reader announcing every character typed at login. Added
  nospeakup to GRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX_DEFAULT, ran update-grub. Did not fully kill it. Had to remove
  the packages outright:
      sudo apt remove espeakup speech-dispatcher -y

  Gone after reboot.

The Attack
      sudo airmon-ng check kill
      sudo airmon-ng start wlan1

Verified monitor mode:
      iwconfig

    wlan1mon confirmed. Scanned, identified target on channel 8, locked on:
      sudo airodump-ng -c 8 --bssid D6:F2:DD:7E:7F:10 -w /tmp/capture wlan1mon

  Client connected organically during capture. No deauth needed. Handshake appeared in three minutes:

      WPA handshake: D6:F2:DD:7E:7F:10

  Ran rockyou against the cap file. Password was intentionally strong so it did not crack. Expected. The
  objective was the capture workflow, not a weak password.

Key Takeaways
  MT7921AU needs firmware that Kali does not include by default. Verify with dmesg before assuming a
  dead adapter.
  Handshake capture requires an active client. EAPOL exchange only happens on authentication.
  Deauth forces it. In this case a client connected naturally.
  A captured handshake is not access. It is offline cracking material. Password strength is the real
  defense.

